<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-06-17T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-06-17T01:00:00-05:00" n="635" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d635">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/14855: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-06-17T13:00:00+07:00">June 17,
                                1942—1 p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received 3:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>720. Sun Fo, President of the Legislative Yuan, in a speech on June 5
                        predicted that after the war “Indochina, Burma and India will regain their
                        sovereignty” and Wu Te-chen, Secretary General of the Kuomintang, in a
                        speech on June 12 several times declared that after the war Burma shall be
                        free. These declarations are representative of Chinese tendency to consider
                        that China shall be the leader of Asiatic peoples.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>